{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why Three Projections?"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Self-attention is fundamentally a question: \"which other positions should this token borrow information from?\" To answer it, each token projects its embedding into three distinct roles — Query, Key, and Value — using three separate learned linear layers."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Query (Q):"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " what this token is looking for."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Key (K):"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " what this token has to offer as a match."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Value (V):"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " the actual content this token contributes when selected."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Having separate projections for the three roles gives the model flexibility to express \"I am searching for X\" (Q) independently of \"I can be found as Y\" (K), which is much more expressive than a single shared representation."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Left: a token embedding x is linearly projected by W_Q, W_K, W_V into Q (red), K (green), V (purple). Scaled dot-product attention flows Q·Kᵀ → ÷√d_k → softmax → ×V → output. Right: database analogy and 'bank approved the loan' attention score bars showing 'approved' and 'loan' receive high weight from 'bank'."
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The Projection Math"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Given an input matrix "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ],
            "text": "X"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " ∈ ℝ"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "^(T×d)"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (T tokens, each of dimension d), the three projections are:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "Q = X W_Q, \\quad K = X W_K, \\quad V = X W_V"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Where "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "W_Q, W_K ∈ ℝ^(d×d_k)"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "W_V ∈ ℝ^(d×d_v)"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". For BERT-base: d = 768, d_k = d_v = 64 (= 768 / 12 heads). The projections shrink the dimension from 768 to 64 per head."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Scaled Dot-Product Attention"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The attention score between query "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "i"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " and key "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ],
            "text": "j"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is their dot product, scaled by "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "inlineMath"
              },
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "1/\\sqrt{d_k}"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to prevent the dot products from growing large (which would push the softmax into saturation regions with near-zero gradients):"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{Attention}(Q, K, V) = \\text{softmax}\\!\\left(\\frac{QK^\\top}{\\sqrt{d_k}}\\right) V"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The softmax converts raw scores into a probability distribution over tokens. The output at each position is a weighted sum of value vectors — the model attends more to tokens whose keys closely match its query."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Implementation in PyTorch"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn as nn\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\nimport math\n\nclass ScaledDotProductAttention(nn.Module):\n    def __init__(self, d_model: int, d_k: int):\n        super().__init__()\n        self.d_k = d_k\n        self.W_Q = nn.Linear(d_model, d_k, bias=False)\n        self.W_K = nn.Linear(d_model, d_k, bias=False)\n        self.W_V = nn.Linear(d_model, d_k, bias=False)\n\n    def forward(self, x, mask=None):\n        # x: (batch, seq_len, d_model)\n        Q = self.W_Q(x)  # (batch, seq_len, d_k)\n        K = self.W_K(x)  # (batch, seq_len, d_k)\n        V = self.W_V(x)  # (batch, seq_len, d_k)\n\n        # Scaled dot-product: (batch, seq_len, seq_len)\n        scores = torch.bmm(Q, K.transpose(1, 2)) / math.sqrt(self.d_k)\n\n        if mask is not None:\n            scores = scores.masked_fill(mask == 0, float(\"-inf\"))\n\n        weights = F.softmax(scores, dim=-1)  # attention distribution\n        output = torch.bmm(weights, V)       # (batch, seq_len, d_k)\n        return output, weights\n\n# Example\nattn = ScaledDotProductAttention(d_model=768, d_k=64)\nx = torch.randn(2, 10, 768)   # batch=2, 10 tokens, d=768\nout, w = attn(x)\nprint(out.shape)   # (2, 10, 64)\nprint(w.shape)     # (2, 10, 10) — attention matrix"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why Scale by √d_k?"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "If Q and K have unit-variance components, then the raw dot product Q·K has variance "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "inlineMath"
              },
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "d_k"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (the sum of d_k unit-variance products). For d_k = 64, scores have standard deviation 8 — large enough to drive softmax toward one-hot distributions and near-zero gradients. Dividing by "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "inlineMath"
              },
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "\\sqrt{d_k}"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " restores unit variance."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\n\nd_k = 64\nq = torch.randn(100, d_k)  # 100 query vectors\nk = torch.randn(100, d_k)  # 100 key vectors\n\nraw_scores = (q * k).sum(dim=-1)          # dot products\nscaled_scores = raw_scores / d_k ** 0.5\n\nprint(f\"raw std:    {raw_scores.std():.2f}\")    # ≈ 8.0 (√64)\nprint(f\"scaled std: {scaled_scores.std():.2f}\")  # ≈ 1.0"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Using PyTorch's Built-in Attention"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In practice, use "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "torch.nn.functional.scaled_dot_product_attention"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " (PyTorch ≥ 2.0), which dispatches to FlashAttention when available and handles masking and dropout efficiently:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import torch\nimport torch.nn.functional as F\n\n# Simulate a single attention head\nbatch, seq, d_k = 2, 10, 64\nQ = torch.randn(batch, seq, d_k)\nK = torch.randn(batch, seq, d_k)\nV = torch.randn(batch, seq, d_k)\n\n# scale=None → uses 1/sqrt(d_k) automatically\nout = F.scaled_dot_product_attention(Q, K, V, scale=None)\nprint(out.shape)  # (2, 10, 64)\n\n# Causal mask for decoder-only usage\nout_causal = F.scaled_dot_product_attention(Q, K, V, is_causal=True)\nprint(out_causal.shape)  # (2, 10, 64)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Key Properties"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Position-equivariant:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " the QKV projections operate identically on every token. Order information comes from positional embeddings, not from the attention equations."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Parallelizable:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " all token projections and all dot products are independent — computed in parallel as matrix multiplications."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "O(T²) cost:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " the attention matrix "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "QKᵀ"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " is T×T, which is quadratic in sequence length. This is the bottleneck for long documents."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Soft lookup:"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " unlike a hash table, attention retrieves a weighted blend of all values, not a single match. This allows the model to express uncertainty and combine information from multiple positions simultaneously."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
}
